ll three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Dyfnaint ap Meurig was born about 1030, in Glynllifon, Caernarfonshire, Wales, his father, Meurig ap Iddig, was 32 and his mother, Mrs Meurig ap Iddig, was 22. He had at least 2 sons with Mrs. Dyfnaint ap Meurig."},"et":{"about 1030–":"umbes 1030–Surnud","1030–Male":"1030–Surnud","1037–Female":"1037–Surnud","1057–Male":"1057–Surnud","1065–Male":"1065–Surnud","1000–Male":"1000–Surnud","1010–Female":"1010–Surnud","about 1030":"umbes 1030","1037":"1037","1057":"1057","1000":"1000","about 1057":"umbes 1057","1010":"1010","1065":"1065","1030":"1030","about 1065":"umbes 1065","Glynllifon, Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Glynllifon, Caernarfonshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1030–":"noin 1030–Kuollut","1030–Male":"1030–Kuollut","1037–Female":"1037–Kuollut","1057–Male":"1057–Kuollut","1065–Male":"1065–Kuollut","1000–Male":"1000–Kuollut","1010–Female":"1010–Kuollut","about 1030":"noin 1030","1037":"1037","1057":"1057","1000":"1000","about 1057":"noin 1057","1010":"1010","1065":"1065","1030":"1030","about 1065":"noin 1065","Glynllifon, Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Glynllifon, Caernarfonshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1030–":"environ 1030–Décédé","1030–Male":"1030–Décédé","1037–Female":"1037–Décédée","1057–Male":"1057–Décédé","1065–Male":"1065–Décédé","1000–Male":"1000–Décédé","1010–Fema